  <h2>The question</h2>
  <p>How do various RNN architectures compare when tasked with next word prediction for morphologically rich languages like Hindi?</p>

  <h2>What I built</h2>
  <p>I tested five different architectures, ranging from vanilla RNNs to stacked BiLSTMs. I developed a custom tokenizer specifically for Hindi to better handle subword units and inflection.</p>

  <h2>What I found</h2>
  <p>Surprisingly, a well-tuned Vanilla RNN beat several LSTM variants in short range prediction. However, BiLSTMs showed a clear ceiling in performance, highlighting the importance of future context in Hindi sentence structure.</p>
